<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,909,2033]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" box="[198,473,1894,1919]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis box="[198,473,1894,1919]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Phaeophila dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as being endophytic, epiphytic on the peduncle of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamouroux (1812: 185)" authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityPageNumber="185" authorityYear="1812" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Polyphysaceae" genus="Acetabularia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dasycladales" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1283,1436,1894,1919]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Acetabularia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lamouroux, J. V. F." box="[151,433,1931,1957]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" pagination="181 - 188" refId="ref7652" refString="Lamouroux, J. V. F. (1812) Extrait d'un memoire sur la classification des Polypiers coralligenes non entierement pierreux. Nouveaux Bulletin des Sciences, par la Societe Philomathique de Paris 3: 181 - 188." type="journal article" year="1812">Lamouroux (1812: 185)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authority="Huber (1893: 332))" authorityName="Huber" authorityPageNumber="332" authorityYear="1893" box="[482,867,1931,1957]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="divaricata">
<emphasis box="[482,631,1932,1957]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">P. divaricata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, J." box="[639,867,1931,1957]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" pagination="265 - 359" refId="ref7391" refString="Huber, J. (1893) Contributions a la connaissance des Chaetophorees epiphytes et endophytes et de leurs affinites. Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, serie 7 16: 265 - 359." type="journal article" year="1893">Huber (1893: 332))</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thyvi, F." box="[883,1023,1931,1957]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" pagination="244 - 264" refId="ref9085" refString="Thyvi, F. (1943) New records of some marine Chaetophoraceae and Chaetosphaeridiaceae for North America. Biological Bulletin 85: 244 - 264." type="journal article" year="1943">Thyvi 1943</bibRefCitation>
) and endolithic, growing on stones and shells (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Kelly, C. J. &amp; Wisor, B. &amp; Bellows, W. K." box="[289,534,1969,1995]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" pagination="789 - 799" refId="ref8255" refString="O'Kelly, C. J., Wisor, B. &amp; Bellows, W. K. (2004) Gene sequence diversity and the phylogenetic position of algae assigned to the genera Phaeophila and Ochlochaete (Ulvophyceae, Chlorophyta) Journal of Phycology 40: 789 - 799. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1529 - 8817.2004.03204. x" type="journal article" year="2004">
O’Kelly 
<emphasis box="[398,459,1969,1994]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
). In the present study, this species was found growing on the thallus of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityYear="1816" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Polyphysaceae" genus="Acetabularia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dasycladales" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="crenulata">A. crenulata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as well as isolated in culture.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894292" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4894292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894292/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" startId="5.[151,246,1880,1901]" targetBox="[197,1400,157,1857]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1880,2003]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1880,1901]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">FIGURE 2:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" box="[281,510,1880,1901]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis box="[281,510,1880,1901]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">Phaeophila dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A: Tufts growing on the thallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityYear="1816" box="[873,1103,1880,1901]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Polyphysaceae" genus="Acetabularia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" order="Dasycladales" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="crenulata">
<emphasis box="[873,1103,1880,1901]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">Acetabularia crenulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(arrows). B: Detail of a tuft with uniseriate filaments composed of cylindrical cells. C: Filaments with cylindrical and spherical cells in 
<emphasis box="[1149,1220,1914,1935]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">in vitro</emphasis>
culture. D: Cells with erect, colorless and sinuous hairs (arrows). E: Detail of the dilated base of the hair (arrow). F: Cells with characteristic intumescences (arrows). G: Detail of a cell with parietal chloroplast with pyrenoids. H: Gametes or spores.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">
A number of studies have reported that the morphology of the filament cells of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" box="[1162,1436,152,177]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis box="[1162,1436,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Phaeophila dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
varies according to the host 
<typeStatus box="[498,554,189,215]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">type</typeStatus>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Thyvi, F." box="[567,728,189,215]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="244 - 264" refId="ref9085" refString="Thyvi, F. (1943) New records of some marine Chaetophoraceae and Chaetosphaeridiaceae for North America. Biological Bulletin 85: 244 - 264." type="journal article" year="1943">Thyvi (1943)</bibRefCitation>
observed that specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" box="[1079,1244,189,214]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis box="[1079,1244,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">P. dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authority="Reinke (1889: 86))" authorityName="Reinke" authorityPageNumber="86" authorityYear="1889" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="engleri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Phaeophila engleri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Reinke, J." box="[244,473,226,252]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="1 - 101" refId="ref8537" refString="Reinke, J. (1889) Algenflora der westlichen Ostsee deutschen Antheils. Eine systematisch-pflanzengeographische Studie. Bericht der Kommission zur wissenschaftlichen Untersuchung der Deutschen Meere in Kiel 6: 1 - 101." type="journal article" year="1889">Reinke (1889: 86))</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
growing on mollusk shells had cells with extremely irregular outlines, forming lateral and vertical papilla and having thickened cell walls. The specimens studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nielsen, R." box="[1241,1430,264,290]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="425 - 438" refId="ref7890" refString="Nielsen, R. (1987.) Marine algae within calcareous shells from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Botany 25: 425 - 438." type="journal article" year="1987">Nielsen (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, however, had filaments whose cells had numerous intumescences, few hairs and cylindrical, cruciform or spherical shapes (
<bibRefCitation author="Nielsen, R." box="[357,516,338,364]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="425 - 438" refId="ref7890" refString="Nielsen, R. (1987.) Marine algae within calcareous shells from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Botany 25: 425 - 438." type="journal article" year="1987">Nielsen 1987</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 10). In the present study, the cultivated specimens grew tufts of filaments having elongated cylindrical cells as well as spherical cells (
<figureCitation box="[856,949,376,402]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,246,1880,1901]" captionTargetBox="[197,1400,157,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-95@5.[180,1416,141,1874]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2: Phaeophila dendroides. A: Tufts growing on the thallus of Acetabularia crenulata (arrows). B: Detail of a tuft with uniseriate filaments composed of cylindrical cells. C: Filaments with cylindrical and spherical cells in in vitro culture. D: Cells with erect, colorless and sinuous hairs (arrows). E: Detail of the dilated base of the hair (arrow). F: Cells with characteristic intumescences (arrows). G: Detail of a cell with parietal chloroplast with pyrenoids. H: Gametes or spores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894292/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="59" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">
The filaments of the specimens analyzed had 1–2 long and sinuous hairs per cell that were continuous with the cell lumen, sometimes with a thickened base (
<figureCitation box="[828,924,452,478]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,246,1880,1901]" captionTargetBox="[197,1400,157,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-95@5.[180,1416,141,1874]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2: Phaeophila dendroides. A: Tufts growing on the thallus of Acetabularia crenulata (arrows). B: Detail of a tuft with uniseriate filaments composed of cylindrical cells. C: Filaments with cylindrical and spherical cells in in vitro culture. D: Cells with erect, colorless and sinuous hairs (arrows). E: Detail of the dilated base of the hair (arrow). F: Cells with characteristic intumescences (arrows). G: Detail of a cell with parietal chloroplast with pyrenoids. H: Gametes or spores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894292/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Thyvi, F." box="[947,1109,452,478]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="244 - 264" refId="ref9085" refString="Thyvi, F. (1943) New records of some marine Chaetophoraceae and Chaetosphaeridiaceae for North America. Biological Bulletin 85: 244 - 264." type="journal article" year="1943">Thyvi (1943)</bibRefCitation>
described specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">P. dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reinke" authorityYear="1889" box="[329,440,490,515]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="engleri">
<emphasis box="[329,440,490,515]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">P. engleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with few hairs, sometimes absent, sinuous or straight, continuous with the lumen of the support-cell, or septate when continuous with the dilated base. Although the presence of hairs is characteristic of the genus, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilkinson, M." box="[499,719,568,594]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="235 - 240" refId="ref9237" refString="Wilkinson, M. (1975) The occurrence of shell-boring Phaeophila species in Britain. British Phycological Journal 10: 235 - 240." type="journal article" year="1975">Wilkinson (1975)</bibRefCitation>
noted that these hairs were not useful characteristics for distinguishing the species for when members of 
<taxonomicName box="[731,916,606,632]" class="Chlorophyceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chaetophorales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="order">Chaetophorales</taxonomicName>
are exposed to different degrees of salinity these hairs can be lost. The hairs apparently have absorption functions, as deduced from experimental cultivation of species of 
<taxonomicName box="[454,627,684,710]" class="Phaeophyceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Phaeophyta" rank="class">Phaeophyceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[688,876,684,710]" class="Chlorophyceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chaetophorales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="order">Chaetophorales</taxonomicName>
in media deficient in certain nutrients (
<bibRefCitation author="Thyvi, F." pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="97 - 110" refId="ref9054" refString="Thyvi, F. (1942) A new species of Ectochaete (Huber) Wille, from woods hole, Massachussetts. Biological Bulletin 83: 97 - 110." type="journal article" year="1942">Thyvi 1942</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">
Reproductive structures (gametes or spores, 
<figureCitation box="[718,809,761,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,246,1880,1901]" captionTargetBox="[197,1400,157,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-95@5.[180,1416,141,1874]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2: Phaeophila dendroides. A: Tufts growing on the thallus of Acetabularia crenulata (arrows). B: Detail of a tuft with uniseriate filaments composed of cylindrical cells. C: Filaments with cylindrical and spherical cells in in vitro culture. D: Cells with erect, colorless and sinuous hairs (arrows). E: Detail of the dilated base of the hair (arrow). F: Cells with characteristic intumescences (arrows). G: Detail of a cell with parietal chloroplast with pyrenoids. H: Gametes or spores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894292/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
) were observed in the cultivated specimens, although it was not possible to identify the cells from which they arose. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="O'Kelly, C. J. &amp; Yarish, C." box="[1115,1431,800,826]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="548 - 558" refId="ref8198" refString="O'Kelly, C. J. &amp; Yarish, C. (1980) Observations on marine Chaetophoraceae (Chlorophyta) I. Sporangial ontogeny in the type species of Entocladia and Phaeophila. Journal of Phycology 16: 548 - 558. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1529 - 8817.1980. tb 03073. x" type="journal article" year="1980">O’Kelly &amp; Yarish (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, reproduction in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hauck (1876: 56)" authorityName="Hauck" authorityPageNumber="56" authorityYear="1876" box="[357,738,838,864]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[357,502,839,864]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Phaeophila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hauck, F." box="[513,738,838,864]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="54 - 57" refId="ref7270" refString="Hauck, F. (1876) Verzeichniss der im Golfe von Triest gesammelten Meeralgen. (Fortsetzung) Osterreichische botanische Zeitschrift 26: 24 - 26, 54 - 57." type="journal article" year="1876">Hauck (1876: 56)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
occurs by way of quadriflagellated zoospores derived simultaneously from multinucleated sporangia; the sporangia develop from vegetative cells with the same morphology and an elongated necks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">
Among the valid 11 species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hauck" authorityYear="1876" box="[679,814,954,979]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[679,814,954,979]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Phaeophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, four were cited for the American Atlantic Ocean; of those, only the type-species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batters" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="P. Crouan &amp; H. Crouan" box="[505,668,993,1018]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Phaeophilaceae" genus="Phaeophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="dendroides">
<emphasis box="[505,668,993,1018]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">P. dendroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) was known from the Brazilian coast, specifically from 
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="6" pageNumber="59">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
(Reis &amp; Yoneshigue-Valentin 1996) and Atol das Rocas (
<bibRefCitation author="Oliveira, E. C. &amp; Ugadim, Y." box="[911,1212,1032,1058]" pageId="6" pageNumber="59" pagination="41 - 44" refId="ref8014" refString="Oliveira, E. C. &amp; Ugadim, Y. (1976) A survey of the marine algae of Atol das Rocas (Brazil) Phycologia 15: 41 - 44. doi: 10.2216 / i 0031 - 8884 - 15 - 1 - 41.1" type="journal article" year="1976">Oliveira &amp; Ugadim 1976</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
